title: Great Otway NP - Plants
description: Including all areas of the Great Otway NP, from Torquay to Princetown.

items.title: Geranium robertianum
items.content_text: Growing at Maits Rest rainforest walk. I think it's a geranium but I can't work out the species. Two photos.

items.title: Australina pusilla subsp. muelleri
items.content_text: Set of four showing male and female flowers.

items.title: Unidentified
items.content_text: We do not know what this plant is.   Tightly clumped circle 40cm in diameter, 10cm high, of shiny green elongated leaves 4-7cm long.  Mass of leaves with lots of flowers hidden under the leaves.  Flowers are hooded, cup-like 3-4cm long with a thick white column inside.  White base with purple hood.  Plant appears to be connected with roots, not bulbs.

items.title: Dipodium roseum s.s.
items.content_text: The only individual of this species observed during the 1.5km circuit walk of the Distillery Creek Nature Trail north of Airey's Inlet in the Great Otway National Park.

items.title: Cassytha melantha
items.content_text: Black sepals are a key feature of this species (hence the name melantha). Pic 3 has a small insect on it, possibly a Hemiptera.

items.title: Correa backhouseana var. backhouseana
items.content_text: This 100m of coastline contains possibly the only extant population of this species on mainland Australia.

items.title: Comesperma ericinum
items.content_text: Really unusual form in this swamp. Only two records locally, 20km either side of this one, and both from about 1890. ID by NW.

items.title: Leptospermum continentale
items.content_text: Verging on L. scoparium on some plants (eg. pic1) but leaves broadest at base and tapering to tip as per L. continentale (see especially pic2). Unusual forms of many species in this swamp.
